om the American social imagination. Recently, however, the authors find that a new kind of unionism-one that more closely resembles a social movement-has begun to develop from the shell of the old labor movement. Looking at the cities of Los Angeles and Las Vegas they point to new practices that are being developed by innovative unions to fight corporate domination, practices that may well signal a revival of unionism and the emergence of a new social imagination in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aBureaucracyxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aBureaucracyzUnited States. 0aIndustrial relationsxUnited States. 0aIndustrial relationszUnited States. 0aLabor movementxUnited States. 0aLabor movementzUnited States. 0aLabor unionsxManagementxUnited States. 0aLabor unionsxSocial aspectsxUnited States. 0aLabor unionsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aLabor unionszUnited StatesxManagement. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh1 aVoss, Kim, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520937710423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520937710.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles